@remark ==================================================================
@Node _INTRODUCTION                                         "Introduction"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Introduction@{fg text}

This application reads AmiNet index files or recent mails as
distributed from a mailserver or recent news published in the
newsgroup '*comp.sys.amiga.archive'. Many mail/news readers
are already supported or can be easily added.

It opens a MUI graphical user interface to select files for
downloading, copying or remembering. Files can be selected
from several input sources into one final list at one or
more sessions. AmiNet directories of no interest can be
excluded by the external program AminetFilter which is
supported within RecentScript.

You can generate an user defined output from the selected
archives. This can be an ARexx/DOS script or simply a text
file. New output configurations can easily be edited, added
and may contain user defined variables which can be altered
within the program.

RecentScript can be started within mail/news readers via
plugin ARexx scripts. Additional Arexx scripts support the
import of the actual mail/article from a running mail/news
reader instance into RecentScript. New plugin and import
scripts can easily be added and are automatically supported
from RecentScript.

This application requires 'MUIRexx' >=V3.0 from ©Russell Leighton
This application requires 'MUI'            from ©Stefan Stuntz
This application requires 'RexxDosSupport' from ©Hartmut Goebel
This application supports 'AminetFilter'   from ©Marcin Orlowski
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _INSTALLATION                                         "Installation"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Installation@{fg text}

This application requires other software to operate.
First install these packages if not already done:

MUI               AmiNet: util/libs/muiXXusr.lha
MUIRexx           AmiNet: dev/mui/MUIRexx_3_0x.lha
RexxDosSupport    AmiNet: util/libs/rexxdossupport.lha


To filter AmiNet directories of no interest install

AminetFilter      AmiNet: comm/misc/AminetFilter.lha



To install RecentScript simply unextract the distribution archive
to the MUIRexx drawer or move the complete RecentScript drawer to
it.

@{b}
RecentScript is written/configured to operate in the directory
'MUIRexx:RecentScript/'. Note that the assign 'MUIRexx:' must lead
to the main directory of MUIRexx!
@{ub}

NOTE: If you want to store the RecentScript directory in another
      location you must edit both RecentScript scripts. You must
      change the definition of the variable 'srcdir' at the
      beginning of both scripts to the desired one.

@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _HOWTOSTART                                           "How to start"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}How to start@{fg text}

NOTE: RecentScript must be installed properly to operate.
      Please read the @{" Installation " link _INSTALLATION} section!

RecentScript must be started under MUIRexx control.

 - WB :

   Simply doubleclick on the supplied icon.

 - CLI:

   MUIRexx:MUIRexx "MUIRexx:RecentScript/RecentScript.rexx [<arg>]" PORT RECENTSCRIPT

   The CLI start allows the user to give an AmiNet index file as
   argument to the script. It will read the specified file at
   startup.

 - ARexx:

   address command 'MUIRexx:MUIRexx "MUIRexx:RecentScript/RecentScript.rexx '<arg>'" PORT RECENTSCRIPT'

   This line starts RecentScript from an ARexx script. The same
   options as with a CLI start applies.

   With the ARexx start it is possible to write plugin scripts
   for mail/news applications to send the mail/news article to
   RecentScript.
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _UI                                                 "User interface"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}User interface@{fg text}

Use the bubble help from MUI to get online help. Leave the mouse
pointer a few seconds still above an object and the help will pop
up.

Load an AmiNet index file or recent mail/news with the upper 'Import'
button. Then select any archive with a doubleclick to move it to
the lower selected file list. You can also multiselect archives and
move them with the 'Add' button to the lower list.

To mark or unmark archives via a search string enter the case
insensitive pattern into the string gadget and click the '+' or
'-' button.


The lower file list contains your selected archives. This 'Selected
Files' list can be saved in AmiNet index format for later use. The
default file 'RecentScript.lst' in the home directory of RecentScript
will be read automatically by RecentScript at the next start. So you
can remember your selected archives for later use.

The other save modes will generate a user configured output. See
at @{" Configs " link _CONFIGS} for a description and their
usage.

The menu bar contains beside the standard items the settings for
the user configured output batch modes.

The 'Quit after save' setting defines whether Recentscript
automatically terminates after saving the lower list.

The AmiNetfilter option allows to exclude AmiNet directories
of no interest. Archives in these directories will not be
displayed by RecentScript if AmiNetFilter is activated. You
must configure the path to the AmiNetFilter program and the
exclude pattern. For description of the exclude pattern see
the documentation of AmiNetFilter by ©Marcin Orlowski. His
programm can be found on AmiNet at 'comm/misc/AminetFilter.lha'.

The menuitem 'Save settings' will save the selected 'Save as'
configuration, the 'Import from' modes, the 'Quit after save'
and the AmiNetFilter settings. At the next start of RecentScript
these values are restored.


Both lists support a right-mouse-button popup-menu. Take a look
at it.

Apology this user interface documentation. I am just to lazy
because I think the user interface of RecentScript is really
easy to understand :-)
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _USAGE                                                       "Usage"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Usage@{fg text}

RecentScript can be used with any application with an ARexx
port or another way to start an user defined command. The
most obvious use is with a mail or newsreader. A received
recent mail or news article from an AmiNet server could be
forwarded to RecentScript to select an interesting archive
for a later download.


To get AmiNet recent mails you have to subscribe to a mailing
list of the AmiNet main server. Send a mail to

 listproc@mail.wustl.edu

with a body text of

  subscribe aminet-weekly your@email.address

to get a weekly recent mail with the uploaded archives or

  subscribe aminet-daily your@email.address

to get a daily recent mail with the uploaded archives.


To get AmiNet recent news articles subscribe to a newsgroup
'*comp.sys.amiga.archive'.
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _PLUGINS                                                   "Plugins"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Plugins@{fg text}

Plugins support the start from RecentScript within another
program. A Plugin is called from the program and extracts
for example the current mail/article to a file and delivers
it as startup parameter to RecentScript.

Plugins reside in the directory 'Plugins/'. Usually a Plugin
must be configured within the program to a function key, menu
entry or button. The configuration and capabilities of the
provided Plugins are explained in the Plugin itself. Please
read them in the directory 'Plugins/'.


This distribution contains these Plugins:

@{" RecentScript.intui " link "/Plugins/RecentScript.intui/Main"} for IntuiNews   (©M.Scheler / M.Stipp)

@{" RecentScript.mm "    link "/Plugins/RecentScript.mm/Main"}    for MailManager (©P.Aliberti)

@{" RecentScript.thor "  link "/Plugins/RecentScript.thor/Main"}  for THOR        (©Ultima Thule Software)

@{" RecentScript.yam "   link "/Plugins/RecentScript.yam/Main"}   for YAM         (©M.Beck)


If you write a new Plugin or enhance an existing one please
let @{" me " link _AUTHOR} know to provide it to all users with the next version
or upload it to AmiNet with a filename following the pattern
'RS_P_xxx.lha'. Thanks!
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _IMPORTERS                                               "Importers"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Importers@{fg text}

Importers support the fetching of data within RecentScript
from an already running instance of another program. An
Importer is selectable via a cycle button beside the
'Import' button and started with the 'Import' button.

An Importer delivers the name of a file to RecentScript which
contains an AmiNet index, for example the currently selected
mail/article from a reader program.

Importers reside in the directory 'Importers/' and are
recognized and supported by RecentScript automatically.


This distribution contains these Importers:

@{" INews.rexx        " link "/Importers/INews.rexx/Main"} for IntuiNews   (©M.Scheler / M.Stipp)

@{" OnlineSearch.rexx " link "/Importers/OnlineSearch.rexx/Main" } Direct search in AmiNet at ftp.wustl.edu

@{" THOR.rexx         " link "/Importers/THOR.rexx/Main" } for THOR        (©Ultima Thule Software)

@{" YAM.rexx          " link "/Importers/YAM.rexx/Main"  } for YAM         (©M.Beck)


If you write a new Importer or enhance an existing one please
let @{" me " link _AUTHOR} know to provide it to all users with the next version
or upload it to AmiNet with a filename following the pattern
'RS_I_xxx.lha'. Thanks!
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _CONFIGS                                                   "Configs"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Configs@{fg text}

Configs define the generated output from RecentScript.
A config will translate the selected files to whatever
you want. This can be a simple text file, ARexx script,
DOS script, HTML source or whatever you want.

Configs reside in the directory 'Configs/' and are
recognized and supported by RecentScript automatically.
A Config is selectable via the cycle button beside the
'Save' button.

Usually a Config must be setup to your needs. This must
be done before the first use via the 'Settings' menu. A
description of the Config is available within RecentScript
via the 'Description' button.


This distribution contains these Configs:

@{" AmFTP Arexx     " link "/Configs/AmFTP ARexx.hlp/Main"    }  Download script for AmFTP

@{" AmFTP BatchWin  " link "/Configs/AmFTP BatchWin.hlp/Main" }  Batchwindow contents for AmFTP

@{" AmigaGuide      " link "/Configs/Amigaguide.hlp/Main"     }  Amigaguide document

@{" Example         " link "/Configs/Example.hlp/Main"        }  A simple text example

@{" HTML            " link "/Configs/HTML.hlp/Main"           }  HTML page with download links

@{" MountFTP        " link "/Configs/MountFTP.hlp/Main"       }  Download script for MountFTP

@{" Spreadsheet CSV " link "/Configs/Spreadsheet CSV.hlp/Main"}  Import format for speadsheet programms

@{" Thor FTP-Mail   " link "/Configs/Thor FTP-Mail.hlp/Main"  }  FTP-EMail-Request for Thor

@{" UMS FTP-Mail    " link "/Configs/UMS FTP-Mail.hlp/Main"   }  FTP-EMail-Request for UMS

@{" YAM FTP-Mail    " link "/Configs/YAM FTP-Mail.hlp/Main"   }  FTP-EMail-Request for YAM


If you @{" write a new Config " link _NEWCONFIGS} or enhance an existing one please
let @{" me " link _AUTHOR} know to provide it to all users with the next version
or upload it to AmiNet with a filename following the pattern
'RS_C_xxx.lha'. Thanks!
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _NEWCONFIGS                                       "Make new Configs"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Make new Configs@{fg text}

RecentScript support your own written Configs. You can define
new Configs by simply creating some ASCII files. They will
appear as new 'Save as' mode within the RecentScript GUI. Your
Config can define new variables that can be altered and saved by
the user within RecentScript by the 'Settings' menu dialog.

To make a new Config first generate a 'xxx.cfg' file with a
text editor in the directory 'Configs/'. From now on it will
be recognized by RecentScript automatically at the next start.


A Config consists of following files:

@{b}/Configs/xxx.cfg@{ub} @{fg highlight}Mandatory@{fg text}

 This file defines the name (xxx) for the Config which is used
 from RecentScript in the menu bar and in the cycle button. 
 The values can be altered and saved by the user via the
 'Settings' menu dialog


 The 1. line defines if the Config should process the '*.readme'
 files as extra entry for each selected archive.
 Possible values:

   0       - Do not generate an entry for a  '*.readme' file
   1       - Generate an entry for a  '*.readme' file


 The 2. line defines the default path and filename for
 saving the output file of RecentScript.
 Examples:

   sys:YourConfig.rexx
   device:dir1/dir2/name.ext


 The 3. line defines whether the script should be processed
 by RecentScript after saving.
 Possible values:

   Ask     - Ask to process the output by RecentScript
   Never   - Never  process the output by RecentScript 
   Always  - Always process the output by RecentScript 


 The 4. line defines the process command for your output. This
 can be any DOS command. It should contain the placeholder '%o'
 which will be replaced by RecentScript with the filename of the
 saved output.
 Example:

   rx %o
   execute %o
   run >NIL: more %o



@{b}/Configs/xxx.var@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 This file defines one or more Config @{" variables " link _VARIABLES}. This should
 be used for values that are different for each user. The values
 can be altered and saved by the user via the 'Settings' menu
 dialog.

 Each variable consists of two lines:

   The 1. line only defines an explanation which is displayed
   within the 'Settings' menu dialog by RecentScript.
   Example:
     Enter your email address


   The 2. line defines the default value to use.
   Example:
     your@email.address

 Each pair of lines define one Config variable. The first
 Config variable can later be referenced  as '%1', the second
 as '%2' and so on.



@{b}/Configs/xxx.intro@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 This file contains the text which is copied to the output at
 first. It may contain only Config @{" variables " link _VARIABLES} %1, %2 etc. which
 will be replaced by the actual values of the Config.



@{b}/Configs/xxx.entry@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 Although this file is optional it should be supplied because
 it makes the real work :-). It contains text which will be
 copied to the output for each entry in the 'Selected Files'
 list. It may contain the entry @{" variables " link _VARIABLES} %a, %c, %d, %n, %s and
 Config @{" variables " link _VARIABLES} %1, %2 etc. which will be replaced by the
 actual values from the entry and the Config configuration.



@{b}/Configs/xxx.extro@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 This file contains the text which is copied to the output at
 last. It may contain only Config @{" variables " link _VARIABLES} %1, %2 etc. which
 will be replaced by the actual values of the Config.



@{b}/Configs/xxx.hlp@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 Although this file is optional it should be supplied because
 it decribes what your Config do. This file contains the
 description the Config. It is  displayed within RecentScript
 in the 'Settings' menu dialog via the button 'Description...'.



@{b}/Configs/xxx.info@{ub} @{fg highlight}Optional@{fg text}

 This file must be an Amiga DOS Project Icon file which is
 added to the output for use from the WorkBench. It should
 contain a appropriate default tool for executing the output.
 Examples:
   rx
   iconx
   more



Look at the provided Configs to get a hint to produce your
own configurations.


If you write a new Config or enhance an existing one please
let @{" me " link _AUTHOR} know to provide it to all users with the next version
or upload it to AmiNet with a filename following the pattern
'RS_C_xxx.lha'. Thanks!
@EndNode



@remark ==================================================================
@Node _VARIABLES                                               "Variables"
@toc Main

@{fg highlight}Variables@{fg text}

RecentScript supports several placeholders which are replaced
with the actual values in the output.


@{b}Config Variables@{ub}

Variables available in files 'xxx.intro', 'xxx.entry', 'xxx.extro':

  If defined in the 'xxx.var' file these placefolders are
  available:

  %1  -  First  Config variable

  %2  -  Second Config variable
  ...



@{b}Entry Variables@{ub}

Variables only available in the 'xxx.entry' file:

  %a  -  Archive age in weeks in stripped format
         Example: '3'

  %A  -  Archive age in weeks with fixed 3 character width
         Example: '  3'

  %c  -  AmiNet short description in stripped format 
         Example: 'Yet Another Recentparser'

  %C  -  AmiNet short description with fixed 44 character width
         Example: 'Yet Another Recentparser                    '

  %d  -  AmiNet directory in stripped format
         Example: 'pix/misc'

  %D  -  AmiNet directory with fixed 10 character width
         Example: 'pix/misc  '

  %n  -  Archive name in stripped format
         Example: 'YAR.lha'

  %N  -  Archive name with fixed 18 character width
         Example: 'YAR.lha           '

  %s  -  Archive size in stripped format 'xK' for KiloByte or 'xM' for MegaByte
         Example: '5K'

  %S  -  Archive size with fixed 4 character width
         Example: '  5K'

@EndNode



